AI Governance
AI Governance addresses the ethical, transparent, and accountable use of AI technologies, intersecting with data governance to ensure data quality and compliance.<SEP>AI governance refers to a framework and process to ensure AI systems function as intended and align with customer expectations and societal laws.

Organizations
Organizations are entities that manage resources and data, often facing challenges in accessing and utilizing dark data effectively.<SEP>Organizations utilize AI governance to calibrate human involvement in AI decision-making, ensuring compliance and management of risks.<SEP>Organizations are entities that seek to leverage data sharing for enhanced analysis, partnerships, and new revenue streams.

Data Governance Program
A traditional data governance program includes overseeing activities like data security, management, and quality in the context of data science and AI.

Machine Learning Model Management
Machine learning model management is an essential part of AI governance that addresses policies and metrics for production models.

AI Ethics
AI ethics encompasses moral principles that define responsibilities and boundaries for action in AI, often discussed alongside AI governance.

MLOps
MLOps is a set of practices that aims to deploy and maintain machine learning models in production reliably and efficiently, integrating the best practices of DevOps into data science.<SEP>MLOps refers to machine learning operations which promotes best practices to enhance AI governance through visibility and automation.<SEP>MLOps is concerned with managing and operationalizing machine learning models, ensuring they function optimally in production environments.<SEP>MLOps is a set of practices that combines machine learning, DevOps, and data engineering to automate and enhance the machine learning lifecycle.<SEP>MLOps refers to the practices and technologies that streamline the operationalization of machine learning models, similar to DataOps but focused on machine learning processes.

Decision-Making Systems
Decision-making systems involve the use of algorithms and AI to make choices, sometimes with minimal human oversight, impacting governance considerations.

Human Oversight
Human oversight involves the participation of individuals in the decision-making process of AI systems to mitigate risks and ensure accountability.

Performance Metrics
Performance metrics measure the effectiveness and accuracy of AI and machine learning models, essential for governance and continuous improvement.

Transparency Metrics
Transparency metrics assess how openly AI algorithms operate and their implications, vital for ethical AI deployment.

Ethical Dilemmas
Ethical dilemmas refer to moral challenges faced in AI governance, requiring clear decision-making frameworks to navigate.

Data Privacy
Data Privacy encompasses the measures taken to protect personal information and ensure compliance with relevant regulations.<SEP>Data Privacy involves ensuring that personal information used in training AI systems is protected from unauthorized access and exploitation.<SEP>Data privacy concerns the appropriate handling and protection of personally identifiable information in the context of AI.

Self-Service Data Initiatives
Self-service data initiatives refer to efforts that enable users to access and analyze data independently, fostering exploration and experimentation within organizations.

Industrialized Data Products
Industrialized data products are scaled and operationalized solutions that are built following strict governance and quality standards to be utilized at scale within businesses.

Data Science
Data science is a multidisciplinary field that utilizes scientific methods, processes, algorithms, and systems to extract insights from structured and unstructured data.

Aequitas
Aequitas is an open-source toolkit developed by the University of Chicago to aid in understanding and mitigating bias in machine learning models.

University of Chicago
The University of Chicago is a prestigious institution known for its research initiatives, including the development of tools and frameworks for responsible AI practices.

Dataiku
Dataiku is a data science and machine learning platform that provides tools for data preparation and analysis, emphasizing model fairness and performance across populations.<SEP>Dataiku is a proprietary data science platform that supports diverse use cases and provides functionalities via drag-and-drop and code interfaces.

AI Governance Strategy
AI Governance Strategy encompasses frameworks and policies designed to ensure ethical and responsible use of artificial intelligence within organizations.

Quality Assurance in Data Products
Quality Assurance in Data Products refers to the commitment to ensuring high standards for data quality and the processes used in developing data products, integrating practices from traditional software development.

Model Management
Model Management is the process of overseeing machine learning models throughout their lifecycle, ensuring they remain accurate and effective in response to changing data over time.

Transparency in AI
Transparency in AI involves making machine learning models explainable and understandable, particularly regarding their decision-making processes and the potential biases they may entail.

Economic Climate
Economic Climate refers to the macroeconomic factors and conditions affecting the business environment, which can influence data availability and model performance.

Continuous Monitoring
Continuous Monitoring is the practice of regularly assessing machine learning models to ensure they perform as intended and remain relevant to business needs.

AI Security
AI Security encompasses practices and models focused on protecting AI systems from various types of attacks and ensuring their integrity and functionality.

AI System
An AI System refers to a software or hardware solution that uses artificial intelligence techniques to perform tasks, often requiring security measures against vulnerabilities.

Adversarial Examples
Adversarial Examples are specially crafted inputs designed to fool AI models into making incorrect predictions, posing significant security threats to machine learning systems.

Evasion Attack
Evasion Attack is a method by which attackers alter input data to deceive AI models, affecting their ability to classify or respond accurately.

Poisoning Attack
Poisoning Attack involves injecting harmful data into the training set of an AI model, leading to compromised model performance and reliability.

Backdoor Attack
A backdoor attack is a malicious manipulation targeting AI models, allowing unauthorized access or control over model inference results.<SEP>Backdoor Attack occurs when malicious modifications are made to an AI model, allowing for covert control under specific conditions that the general user cannot detect.

Data Integrity
Data Integrity focuses on maintaining consistent data across systems while preventing unauthorized changes.<SEP>Data Integrity involves maintaining the accuracy and consistency of data over its entire lifecycle, a key concern in the context of AI security.<SEP>Data Integrity refers to the accuracy and consistency of data over its lifecycle, critical for reliable data analysis and reporting.

Model Confidentiality
Model Confidentiality refers to protecting the proprietary information, such as training models, from unauthorized access or exposure.

Model Robustness
Model Robustness indicates an AI system's resilience against adversarial inputs and its ability to maintain performance under various conditions.

AI & ML foundations
AI & ML foundations is a category that encompasses the fundamental principles, theories, and practices related to artificial intelligence and machine learning, including their applications and security.

AI Attacks
AI Attacks refer to various methods employed by malicious actors to compromise the integrity and performance of AI systems, including evasion, poisoning, and backdoor attacks.

AI Attack Mitigation
AI Attack Mitigation includes strategies and techniques used to prevent, detect, and respond to security threats against AI systems, ensuring their reliability and safety.

AI Model Security
AI Model Security focuses on protecting the machine learning models from unauthorized access, manipulation, and theft, ensuring that models remain confidential and secure.

AI Architecture Security
AI Architecture Security involves establishing secure frameworks and methodologies for designing and implementing AI systems to protect against various vulnerabilities.

AI Transparency
AI Transparency refers to the degree to which the operations and decision-making processes of AI systems are clear and understandable to users and stakeholders, critical for trust and security.

Healthcare
Healthcare represents a critical domain where AI applications can greatly impact patient safety and treatment outcomes, necessitating robust AI security measures.

Transportation
Transportation is another domain where AI technologies are increasingly implemented, making security concerns paramount due to risks in safety and reliability.

Surveillance
Surveillance encompasses AI applications used in monitoring and security, presenting significant ethical concerns and security risks that must be addressed.

Intrusion Detection System (IDS)
Intrusion Detection System (IDS) is a security solution that monitors network traffic for suspicious activity and potential threats, often using AI for improved detection.

AI-Based Detection Tools
AI-Based Detection Tools refer to technologies that utilize artificial intelligence to identify and respond to security threats in real-time, critical for safeguarding systems.

Transparent AI Systems
Transparent AI Systems are designed to be understandable and accountable, ensuring that their decision-making processes are clear to users, enhancing security and trust.

AI-as-a-Service (AIaaS)
AI-as-a-Service (AIaaS) refers to services provided by AI service providers for model training and inference, utilizing open APIs for applications like image and voice recognition.

neural network model
A neural network model is a computational structure consisting of parameters that can perform tasks such as recognition and classification based on input data.

model stealing
Model stealing involves attacks where an attacker attempts to extract or replicate the parameters and training data of a machine learning model.

adversarial training
Adversarial training is a defensive technique in which adversarial examples are used alongside regular data during the training of a machine learning model to enhance its robustness against attacks.

network distillation
Network distillation is a technology that combines multiple deep neural networks (DNNs) during training to improve model robustness and reduce susceptibility to attacks.

evasion attack
An evasion attack targets AI systems by manipulating input data to deceive the system's function while otherwise appearing normal.

poisoning attack
Poisoning attacks involve manipulating training data to compromise the integrity of the learning process of a model.

backdoor attack
A backdoor attack is characterized by the insertion of hidden manipulations in the model, which can be triggered by specific inputs to control the model's outputs.

input reconstruction
Input reconstruction involves altering input samples during inference to defend against evasion attacks while maintaining the model's normal classification performance.

training data filtering
Training data filtering is a technique to purify training data sets from potential poisoning by identifying and removing compromised data points.

DNN verification
DNN verification refers to the methods used for validating properties of deep neural network models, checking against adversarial examples and function attributes.

AI Security Attacks
AI Security Attacks refer to various malicious strategies aimed at compromising artificial intelligence models, including evasion, poisoning, and backdoor attacks.

model extraction attack
A model extraction attack is a specific type of model stealing where an attacker attempts to reconstruct a machine learning model by querying it and analyzing responses.

adversarial example detection
Adversarial example detection techniques are designed to identify inputs that have been manipulated to deceive AI models during inference.

intellectual property theft
Intellectual property theft in AI refers to the unauthorized appropriation of proprietary model parameters or training data.

adversarial training methods
Adversarial training methods are techniques that enhance a model’s resilience against adversarial examples by systematically integrating these examples into the training dataset.

cloud service providers
Cloud service providers are companies that offer cloud computing services, including infrastructure for AI model training and deployment.

deep neural networks (DNNs)
Deep neural networks (DNNs) are a class of machine learning models that consist of multiple layers to extract features and make predictions based on input data.

model robustness
Model robustness refers to the ability of a machine learning model to maintain performance despite manipulations or adversarial inputs.

reinforcement learning
Reinforcement learning is an area of ML where agents learn to make decisions by receiving rewards or penalties based on their actions.

defensive technologies
Defensive technologies refer to methods developed to protect AI models from various attacks, including adversarial attacks and data poisoning.

DNN pruning
DNN pruning is a technique used to simplify a deep neural network by removing certain neurons while retaining the model's overall functionality.

Adversarial Machine Learning (ML)
Adversarial ML refers to techniques and methods used to attack machine learning models by exploiting vulnerabilities such as backdoors and evasion strategies.

Private Aggregation of Teacher Ensembles (PATE)
PATE is a defense technology that segments training data for individual model training to enhance privacy in AI systems.

Differentially Private Protection
Differentially private protection is a method that introduces noise to data or models to safeguard privacy during AI model training.

Model Watermarking
Model watermarking embeds unique identifiers within models, allowing detection of theft or unauthorized replication.

Model Detectability
Model detectability encompasses techniques ensuring AI models can be checked for vulnerabilities using adversarial detection methods.

Model Verifiability
Model verifiability ensures that deep neural networks (DNNs) meet security requirements through certified verification practices.

Model Explainability
Model explainability describes efforts to make the decision-making processes of AI systems understandable and interpretable for users.

Model Pruning
Model pruning is a technique in machine learning that removes unnecessary neurons from a model while preserving its functions to reduce vulnerabilities.

Evasion Attacks
Evasion attacks are designed to fool an AI model into misclassifying inputs by exploiting its vulnerabilities.

Poisoning Attacks
Poisoning attacks involve injecting malicious data into the training set to manipulate the outcomes of the AI model.

DNN Models
Deep Neural Networks (DNNs) are a class of machine learning models known for their complexity and capability in tasks such as image and voice recognition.

AI Systems
AI systems encompass a variety of applications that utilize artificial intelligence technologies for decision-making and automation.

Training Data
Training data is a dataset used to train models in machine learning, which is crucial for the accuracy and effectiveness of the model.

Security Tests
Security tests are evaluations conducted to assess the robustness and safety of AI models against various attacks before deployment.

Adversarial Training Technologies
Adversarial training technologies involve re-training models with adversarial examples to improve their robustness against attacks.

Explainable AI
Explainable AI refers to methods and techniques in AI that make the outputs and decision processes of AI models understandable to human users.<SEP>Explainable AI seeks to make the decision-making processes of AI systems transparent and understandable to users.

Model Output Integrity
Model output integrity refers to the accuracy and reliability of predictions made by AI models after processing input data.

EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)
The GDPR is a regulation in EU law on data protection and privacy in the European Union and the European Economic Area, designed to protect individuals' data.

AI systems
AI systems are artificial intelligence technologies that can perform tasks that typically require human intelligence, such as learning, reasoning, and problem-solving.

autonomous driving
Autonomous driving refers to the use of AI systems to enable vehicles to navigate and drive without human intervention.

customer reimbursement capability
Customer reimbursement capability pertains to the ability of a system to process refunds to customers, ensuring fairness and accuracy in its operations.

HR department
An HR department is a division within an organization that manages employee-related processes, including hiring, training, and managing workforce diversity.

security mechanisms
Security mechanisms are protocols and measures put in place to protect information systems from unauthorized access and threats.

Statistics
Statistics is a branch of mathematics involved in the collection, analysis, interpretation, presentation, and organization of data, forming the theoretical foundation of traditional machine learning methods.

Machine Learning (ML)
Machine Learning is a subset of artificial intelligence that involves the use of algorithms and statistical models to enable computers to perform tasks without explicit instructions.

Natural Language Processing
Natural Language Processing (NLP) is a field of AI that enables computers to understand, interpret, and respond to human language in a valuable way.

Voice Recognition
Voice recognition is a technology that enables a computer to identify and process human voices into understandable language commands.

Image Recognition
Image recognition is a technology that enables AI systems to identify and categorize objects within images using deep learning methods.

Information Retrieval
Information retrieval is the process of obtaining information system resources that are relevant to an information need from a collection of those resources.

Biological Information Recognition
Biological information recognition refers to the use of AI and machine learning to analyze and interpret biological data, such as genomic or protein data.

Local Interpretable Model-Agnostic Explanations (LIME)
LIME is a method designed to provide interpretability to machine learning models, helping to explain predictions made by complex models.

Customer Reimbursement
Customer reimbursement refers to the process by which companies refund customers for products or services, requiring fairness and transparency in the process.

Prejudice in AI Models
Prejudice in AI models refers to the biases that can arise in AI algorithms due to biased training data, affecting the model outcomes and decisions.

Government Regulatory Bodies
Government regulatory bodies are organizations responsible for creating and enforcing rules and policies in various sectors to ensure safety, reliability, and fairness.

Data Lake
A data lake is a centralized repository that allows organizations to store large volumes of structured and unstructured data for analysis and processing.<SEP>Data Lake is a storage repository that holds vast amounts of raw data in its native format until it is needed.

Data Analysts
Data Analysts are professionals who explore and analyze data to identify patterns, trends, and insights from the data lake.

Data Scientists
Data Scientists utilize data lakes to access raw and enriched data for building machine learning models and performing analytics.

Machine Learning Engineers
Machine Learning Engineers leverage data lakes to train models and develop predictive analytics solutions.

Jupyter Notebooks
Jupyter Notebooks is an open-source web application that allows users to create and share documents containing live code, equations, visualizations, and narrative text.

TensorFlow
TensorFlow is an open-source framework for machine learning that is widely used for building deep learning applications.

PyTorch
PyTorch is an open-source machine learning library used for applications such as computer vision and natural language processing.

Customer 360
Customer 360 refers to the comprehensive view of a customer’s behavior, preferences, and needs achieved by merging data sets.

Digital Twins
Digital Twins are virtual replicas of physical objects or systems that utilize data lakes for simulation and analysis.

Data Monetization
Data Monetization is the practice of generating revenue through data by sharing it with other parties or using it to enhance business operations.<SEP>Data Monetization is the process through which organizations generate revenue or value from their data assets.<SEP>Data Monetization refers to the process of commercializing data to generate additional revenue streams for businesses across various industries.

Data Mesh
Data Mesh is a modern architecture approach that emphasizes treating data as a product, enabling data domain teams to build and share data products over time.<SEP>Data Mesh is an architectural approach that treats data as a product, allowing organizations to improve data management across various domains and enabling decentralized ownership.<SEP>Data Mesh is an emerging data architecture approach that decentralizes data ownership and promotes self-service for data access and governance.<SEP>Data Mesh is an emerging data architecture that decentralizes data ownership and accountability, allowing companies to treat data as a product and maximize data value.

Conversational AI Applications
Conversational AI Applications utilize large language models and can be enhanced by integrating data from data lakes.

Consumption Use Cases
Consumption Use Cases refer to various methods by which organizations and users can access, analyze, and derive value from data stored in a data lake.

Descriptive Analytics
Descriptive Analytics involves using data to create dashboards and reports to summarize past and present trends.

Business Intelligence Tools
Business Intelligence Tools are software applications used by organizations to collect, analyze, and present business data.

Exploratory Data Analysis
Exploratory Data Analysis is a process of examining data sets to summarize their main characteristics often using visual methods.

Ad-hoc Querying
Ad-hoc Querying allows users to create custom queries to explore specific aspects of data dynamically.

Data Profiling
Data Profiling is the process of examining the data available in an existing data source to collect statistics and information about that data.

Data Visualization
Data Visualization involves creating graphical representations of information and data to facilitate understanding.

Data Monetization Strategies
Data Monetization Strategies are approaches used by organizations to generate revenue from their data assets.

Data Quality
Data Quality refers to the condition of a dataset and how it meets the requirements or standards for accuracy and completeness.<SEP>Data Quality refers to the overall accuracy, completeness, and reliability of data, which is essential for effective data governance and analytics.<SEP>Data Quality refers to the degree of accuracy, consistency, completeness, reliability, and relevance of the data collected, stored, and used within an organization.

Real-time Data Hub
A Real-time Data Hub is a data architecture that allows for the continuous processing and availability of data.

API Gateway
An API Gateway is a server that acts as an intermediary for requests from clients seeking services from backend systems.

Data Sources Trends
Data Sources Trends is a category that encompasses the various classifications and trends associated with data and its attributes.

Big Data
Big Data refers to large volumes of data that also includes characteristics of speed, variety, and complexity.

Dark Data
Dark Data is information collected during regular business activities that remain unused or unanalyzed.<SEP>Dark Data represents data that is not collected or utilized, often seen as an untapped resource in organizations.<SEP>Dark data refers to data that organizations collect but do not utilize, often considered outdated or inaccessible due to various limitations.

Modern Data Strategy
Modern Data Strategy encompasses approaches to effectively manage all types of data, including dark data.<SEP>Modern Data Strategy involves analyzing data sources, consumption, and analytical goals to determine optimal data architecture for an organization.

IoT sensor data
IoT sensor data refers to data generated from Internet of Things devices, often contributing to dark data.

Lakes
Data lakes are storage repositories that hold vast amounts of raw data in its native format until it is needed.

Data integration processes
Data integration processes involve the methods through which varying types of data, including dark data, are combined and analyzed.

Artificial Intelligence
Artificial Intelligence (AI) encompasses technologies that enable machines to analyze and learn from data, holding potential to transform business practices.<SEP>Artificial Intelligence refers to the simulation of human intelligence in machines, which can leverage dark data for better decision-making.

Machine data
Machine data refers to data generated by machines, growing rapidly and playing a critical role in the understanding of dark data.

Customer Behavior Data
Customer Behavior Data includes records of activities and interactions of customers, often part of dark data.

Server Log Files
Server log files are records of events that occur within a server, serving as a source of potential dark data.

Network Transactions
Network Transactions involve activities conducted through a network, contributing to dark data when unexploited.

GPS Networks
GPS Networks involve data related to global positioning, often classified as dark data if not used effectively.

Cloud Services
Cloud Services refer to computing services provided over the internet, which can generate both active and dark data.

Industrial Networks
Industrial Networks consist of data from industrial systems that may also contribute to dark data challenges.

Produce & Aquire
Produce & Aquire is a category that relates to the processes and strategies involved in obtaining and utilizing data.

Data
Data refers to the various types of information generated, collected, and used within systems and applications across organizations.<SEP>Data refers to various forms of information collected by organizations, which can be valuable but often remains underutilized.

Structured Data
Structured Data is data that is organized in a predefined manner, making it easily searchable and analyzable.

Semi-Structured Data
Semi-Structured Data is data that does not conform to a fixed schema but contains tags or markers to separate data elements.

Unstructured Data
Unstructured Data is data that lacks a specific format or structure, often making it more challenging to analyze.

Relational Data
Relational Data is a type of data that is structured to recognize relations among entities and is organized in tables.

External Data
External Data refers to information derived from outside an organization, often used to enhance internal analyses.

Master Data
Master Data includes the critical entities of an organization that are essential for its operations and analytics.

Transactional Data
Transactional Data is data that is generated from transactions, often dynamic and changing frequently.

Time Series Data
Time Series Data is data indexed in time order, often used for tracking changes over time.

Fast Data
Fast Data refers to data that is generated and processed at high speeds, often in real-time scenarios.

Streaming Data
Streaming Data is a type of data that is continuously generated by different sources and processed in real-time.

Data Exhaust
Data Exhaust is a term used to describe the byproducts of data production, often considered dark data.

Organizational Data
Organizational Data refers to data that is generated within an organization's daily operations.

Data Analytics
Data Analytics refers to the process of examining data sets to derive insights and inform decision-making.

Financial Transactions
Financial Transactions include records of all financial activities conducted by an organization.

Employees
Employees represent individuals working within an organization who generate and utilize data in various capacities.

Decision Making
Decision Making is the cognitive process of choosing among alternatives based on data analysis.

Artificial Intelligence Systems
Artificial Intelligence Systems are technologies that use algorithms and computing power to perform tasks that usually require human intelligence.

Consultancy
Consultancy firms are external entities that help organizations analyze and leverage their data, potentially including dark data.

AI-Powered Analytics Tools
AI-powered analytics tools are advanced software applications that utilize artificial intelligence to process and analyze vast amounts of data efficiently.

Business Leaders
Business leaders are decision-makers within organizations who are responsible for harnessing data and improving data management practices.

Data Governance
Data Governance involves managing and overseeing data assets to ensure their quality, privacy, compliance, and proper use within organizations.

Data Security
Data Security focuses on protecting data assets, ensuring their confidentiality, integrity, and availability throughout their lifecycle.

Data Infrastructure
Data Infrastructure encompasses the systems and components necessary to manage and store data, serving as the foundation for analytics and data-driven decision-making in organizations.<SEP>Data Infrastructure includes the tools and systems used for data storage, processing, and analysis.<SEP>Data Infrastructure refers to the foundational technological architecture and frameworks that enable data storage, processing, and management for organizations.<SEP>Data Infrastructure refers to the systems and technologies that enable data storage, processing, and analytics, including edge computing and cloud solutions.

Edge Computing
Edge Computing allows data processing to occur near the source of data generation, enhancing real-time responsiveness and minimizing transfer costs.

Fog Computing
Fog Computing extends cloud capabilities to the edge of the network, creating an intermediary layer for efficient data management.

Hybrid Analytics Solutions
Hybrid Analytics Solutions combine various computing environments to provide comprehensive data analysis, integrating edge and cloud data.

Data Catalogs
Data Catalogs are centralized repositories that organize metadata and information about an organization's data assets, crucial for effective data governance.

DevOps
DevOps combines software development and IT operations, aiming to shorten development life cycles and deliver high-quality software more frequently, sharing principles with DataOps.<SEP>DevOps focuses on automating software development and deployment to enhance collaboration and efficiency in IT processes.

DataOps
DataOps emphasizes data integration, quality, and delivery, tailored to support data-driven organizations in their workflows.<SEP>DataOps refers to a set of principles and practices that enhance the speed, agility, and quality of data and analytics solutions through improved collaboration and efficiency among data teams.

Open Neural Network Exchange (ONNX)
ONNX is a format that supports interoperability of machine learning models across different frameworks and engines.

Active Metadata Management
Active Metadata Management involves continuously updating and enriching metadata to support data management and governance activities in real-time.

Compliance
Compliance refers to adhering to laws, regulations, standards, and ethical practices regarding data management and usage.

Data Fabric
Data Fabric is one of the three important emerging data architectures alongside Data Mesh and Data Lakehouse, emphasizing integration and management of data across various environments.

Data Lakehouse
Data Lakehouse is a modern data architecture that combines the benefits of both data lakes and data warehouses, optimizing data management and retrieval.<SEP>Data Lakehouse is a unified platform for data storage that incorporates the benefits of data lakes and data warehouses.

Healthcare and Life Sciences
"Healthcare and Life Sciences encompass industries focused on health-related data, impacting patient care and drug development.'

Data Platform Team
Data Platform Team is responsible for managing the underlying data platform and governance related to data product development within organizations.

Domain Data Team
Domain Data Team comprises individuals who use data platforms to build, consume, and manage data products within their domain.

Self-Service Data Platform
Self-Service Data Platform refers to tools and capabilities enabling domain teams to access and use data securely without centralized bottlenecks.

Snowflake
Snowflake is a cloud data warehouse platform often used as a self-service data platform for data management in organizations.<SEP>Snowflake is a cloud-based data platform that enables organizations to share and manage data securely without moving it, providing real-time access and control over permissions.

Delta Lake
Delta Lake is a storage file format that enhances the management of data within data lake setups for better data versioning and access.<SEP>Delta Lake is an open-source storage layer that brings reliability to data lakes and is used in conjunction with Delta Sharing for data management.

Prophecy
Prophecy is a tool that offers a self-serve platform built on top of data lakehouses, designed for building, publishing, and discovering data products.<SEP>Prophecy is a tool utilized for data virtualization, enabling access to data from lakes or transactional systems in a self-service manner.

Data-as-a-Product
Data-as-a-Product is a concept that focuses on making data products easily discoverable, understandable, and usable throughout an organization.

Governance
Governance in data management refers to the policies and processes established to oversee data quality and security.<SEP>Governance in the context of data refers to the policies, standards, and processes that ensure the proper management and use of data within organizations.<SEP>Governance in the context of DataOps pertains to the frameworks and practices that ensure data is managed effectively and securely across organizations.

Security
Security encompasses the measures and practices implemented to protect data from unauthorized access, breaches, and vulnerabilities.<SEP>Security involves the measures taken to protect data from unauthorized access and corruption during storage or transmission.<SEP>Security in DataOps focuses on the measures and protocols to protect data throughout its lifecycle, ensuring compliance and safeguarding sensitive information.

Data Domain Strategy
Data Domain Strategy is a planned approach to define and manage the specific domains or areas of responsibility for data within an organization.

Decentralization
Decentralization refers to the distribution of authority and responsibility for data management across different teams or domains within an organization, as opposed to centralized control.

Data Consumption
Data Consumption is the process of using data by various stakeholders for analysis, reporting, and decision-making.<SEP>Data Consumption relates to how data is accessed and utilized by various stakeholders within an organization for analytical and operational purposes.

Data Transformation
Data Transformation involves the processes and methods used to convert data from one format or structure to another to meet specific analytical needs.<SEP>Data Transformation is the stage where extracted data is transformed into a suitable format for analysis or processing.

Data Products
Data Products are outputs or artifacts created from datasets that provide value through analytics, insights, or direct application in business processes.<SEP>Data Products represent various types of data sets that can be sold or shared with businesses for operational improvement.

Federated Governance
Federated Governance refers to a structured approach to managing data access and security across multiple domains within an organization.<SEP>Federated Governance refers to a system of governance that empowers decentralized teams while ensuring overall compliance and security of data management policies.

User Experience
User Experience in data contexts focuses on how end-users interact with data products and platforms, aiming for an intuitive and helpful user interface.

Data Mesh Architecture
Data Mesh Architecture refers to a decentralized approach to data management where data is treated as a product, empowering domain teams to own and manage their data.

Starburst
Starburst is an analytics engine for Data Mesh architecture, providing access to distributed data and enabling self-service analytics.

Trino
Trino is an open-source distributed engine that can process SQL queries across various data storage solutions, forming the foundation of Starburst.

Databricks Lakehouse Federation
Databricks Lakehouse Federation enables data governance and querying of data across multiple platforms without moving data to a data lakehouse.

Immuta
Immuta is a platform that automates access control to analytical datasets in the cloud, focusing on data governance.

Data Product Teams
Data Product Teams are responsible for managing and owning the data products within an organization, ensuring effective governance and security.

Access Control Policies
Access Control Policies are rules that govern who can view or modify specific data within a Data Mesh architecture.

Self-Serve Platform
Self-Serve Platform is a system or tool that allows users to retrieve and utilize data without needing extensive technical expertise or centralized governance.

Data Virtualization Tools
Data Virtualization Tools are solutions that provide access to data stored across multiple sources without the need to physically consolidate the data.

Transactional System
Transactional System refers to systems that manage and store data from business transactions, providing real-time operational data.

Federated Governance and Security
Federated Governance and Security involves decentralized but consistent management of data access and policies across different domains in an organization.

Policy as Code
Policy as Code is an approach where policy definitions are managed as code to facilitate automation and consistency in policy enforcement.

Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)
Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC) is a model for managing user permissions based on attributes such as roles, policies, and resource characteristics.

Data Use Agreements
Data Use Agreements are formal agreements that stipulate how data can be accessed and used, ensuring compliance and governance in data sharing.

Analytics Engine
Analytics Engine is a component or tool that processes and analyzes data to provide insights and support decision-making based on data analysis.

Physical Data Products
Physical data products are datasets that have been produced, stored, and made available in a data marketplace for consumption.

Virtual Data Products
Virtual data products integrate data from multiple sources to create on-demand views, which can be published in a data marketplace.

Stored Queries
Stored queries refer to SQL queries that can be published as services and executed on demand, producing data products.

Analytical Products
Analytical products include BI reports, dashboards, and machine learning models, serving as outcomes derived from data products.

Data Domain Teams
Data domain teams are responsible for consuming and integrating data products into new pipelines, fostering the creation of additional data products.

Databricks Delta Tables
Databricks Delta tables can be utilized as data products that are published and consumed within a Data Mesh framework.

Data Marketplace
A data marketplace is a platform where various data products are available for consumption, allowing users to discover and use data effectively.

Data Portal
A data portal is a user interface that supports the discovery, documentation, and accessibility of data products in a marketplace.

Data Catalog
A data catalog is a system used to publish and make data discoverable, integrating tags, names, and documentation to facilitate data access and utilization.

Data Sharing Platform
A data sharing platform enables users to share and access data products securely and efficiently, acting as a conduit for collaboration.

BI Reports
Business Intelligence (BI) reports are analytical products that present business data in a meaningful way to support decision-making processes.

Dashboards
Dashboards are visual displays of data that aggregate and present multiple data points for monitoring and analysis.

Predictive Machine Learning Models
Predictive machine learning models are analytical products designed to forecast future outcomes based on historical data patterns.

Prescriptive Machine Learning Models
Prescriptive machine learning models provide recommendations for actions to optimize outcomes based on data analysis.

Recommendation Engines
Recommendation engines are systems that suggest products or content to users based on data analysis of preferences and behavior.

Chat Bots
Chat bots are AI-driven tools that interact with users to provide responses and support, serving as an interface for accessing data products.

Automation Bots
